2 NEW SECTION. Section 8. Governing body review of petition. (1) The governing body OF THE
3 LOCAL GOVERNMENT may, within 60 days of receiving the petition, take the action called for in the petition. If the
4 action is taken, the question need not be submitted to the electors. If the county election administrator has
5 already certified the ballot issue pursuant to [section 9], the results of the election are void.
6 (2) If the governing body does not within 60 days take the proposed action and the ballot issue is
7 certified by the county election administrator, then the question must be submitted to the electors at the election
8 specified in the petition.
9
10 NEW SECTION. Section 9. Submission of signatures -- certification -- election. (1) Signed
11 sheets or sections of petitions with original signatures must be:
12 (a) collected and filed with the official responsible for the registration of electors in the county in
13 which the signatures were obtained within 90 days of the date of the notice that the petition was approved as to
14 form pursuant to [section 4]; and
15 (b) submitted no later than 4 weeks before the certification date specified in subsection (2) of this
16 section.
17 (2) The county election administrator shall certify a local government ballot issue for a local
18 government election no later than 85 days before the election.
19 (3) Subject to [section 7(1)] and subsections (1) and (2) of this section, an election on an approved
20 petition containing sufficient signatures held pursuant to [sections 1 through 13] must be conducted in
21 conjunction with the local government's next election held in accordance with Title 13, chapter 1, part 4.
22 However, if the petition requests a special election, is signed by at least 25% of the qualified electors, and
23 otherwise complies with the requirements of subsections (1) and (2) of this section, a special election must be
24 held on the date specified in the petition. In order to determine the number of signatures needed on a petition to
25 meet the percentage requirements of this subsection (3), the number of electors must be calculated as provided
26 in [section 4(2)].
